Food has been the main driver of European inflation
The acceleration in inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
November's price increases were higher than expected in 13 euro area countries, with annual inflation of 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, the EU statistics office in Luxembourg reported.
The official forecast gave only a 3 percent chance, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the US, UK and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not cut the key interest rate, saying that a reduction would lead to an inflationary spiral with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment.
The ECB wants to keep inflation below but close to 2%.
One analyst says the ECB is in the 22nd trap: "to talk down" inflation so that it does not have to act on it later.
In Germany, November inflation of 3.3 percent is a 12-year high; in Spain, it rose from 3.6 percent to 4.1 percent.
Eurozone inflation was driven by soaring food and energy prices.
Wheat futures have risen 88 percent, and soybean prices have also reached their highest level since 1973.
The price of cooking oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
The world market price of oil has risen 52 percent this year, and last month a barrel of black gold was worth nearly $100.
The ECB forecasts that inflation will jump from 2.1% this year to 2.5% in 2008, but will fall to 1.9% in 2009.
Analysts expect 12-month inflation to remain at around 3 percent for the next three to four months, but the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
