Many places are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections have been reported in hospitals, mainly due to the improper use of antibiotics.
Hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding, and overwork of staff do not help to stop infections, says the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Center.
Many places are also saving on disinfectants.
Recently, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department at St. John's Hospital.
A man who was in a serious accident has been shown to have antibiotic-resistant bacteria.
The patient has been isolated.
A similar infection occurred here earlier this year.
A seriously injured car accident survivor was discharged from the hospital, but soon afterward he returned with an MRSA infection, and an important surgery was not performed because of the bacteria in his system.
As of December 10 this year, 1,094 hospital infections caused by MDR-CoVs have been reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that this number of infections caused by MDR-CoVs are definitely registered in hospitals, and the rest are unknown.
About two thirds of the infections (683) were caused by MRSA, or methicillin-oxacillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
Staphylococcus aureus (SA) is carried in the nose by one third of people without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e. g. strep throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) respond well to antibiotics and are curable.
However, when antibiotics are used in excess or inadequately, bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop into highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria that spread rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In particular, temporary or permanent immune system failure can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or sepsis, in weakened, elderly, or underweight patients.
According to the medical director of St. John's Hospital, there is nothing unusual about MRSA infection, as such infections are part of the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the common cold, MRSA is not there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where they do not test for the presence of the pathogen.
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate such patients, the nursing staff provides rubber gloves and masks, and we have the right antibiotics to treat them", said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to hospital are screened for MRSA, but this does not always prevent infection.
It's not fashion to sample
The vast majority of MRSA hospital infections are preventable, but current hospital conditions and conditions at home are not conducive to preventing the development and spread of MDR-TBs, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is typically found in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor patients who are admitted and isolate patients with MRSA immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
The fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these studies also plays a role.
Most cases are detected when a patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the chief medical officer of the Epidemiological Center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are national guidelines for the treatment of individual infections and conditions.
Efforts should be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological studies should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but this is not always followed by hospitals.
Microbiological samples are even less common in outpatient and primary care, said Böröcz Karolina.
They Save on Disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another through the transmission of healthcare professionals.
So there's a huge role for hand washing, gloves, wearing masks, but there are also major gaps in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by droplet infection, contact, but in home hospital conditions, it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, hospital wards are often overcrowded, with beds often very close together, even though epidemiologically speaking, patients should be at least five feet [1.5 m] apart.
Unfortunately, Karolina Böröcz noted, hospitals in disadvantaged financial situations also have a low cost of disinfectants, few nurses, and many patients, making them even more likely to develop infections.
Karolina Böröcz says that where appropriate precautions are taken, fewer cases of such infections are detected or the spread of the disease can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurance companies, so they're fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has included prevention and reduction of MRSA in its programme.
The programme appears to be a success, with reported data showing a decreasing trend in MRSA infections in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has priorities to prevent the emergence of multi-drug resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
