Political Capital: Hungarian Guard raised the risk of the country
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August with the support of the Jobbik Movement for Hungary, have raised the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysing Division of Political Capital.
The company's "risk warning" stated that the biggest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that "with the deterioration of the ethnic tensions between the Gypsy and non-Gypsy population in Hungary, violent ethnic clashes may develop in the short term".
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to be aimed at provoking such an act, the research institute added.
As they wrote, this can be attributed to one of the main omissions of Hungarian politicians: "public discussion of the Roma issue was left to representatives of radical and extreme political groups, who could build a political strategy against Gypsy-Hungarian".
This, they say, deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, empowers extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflict.
In addition, the research institute says that the activities of the Hungarian Guard, under the influence of the great attention of the national and international media, "significantly damaged the image of Hungary abroad, especially regarding the confidence in the stability of the country and its democratic development".
It is recalled that, as part of the reorganisation of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, which has gained increasing publicity and momentum since autumn 2006, several self-proclaimed 'national self-defense' organisations have been established in Hungary since summer 2007.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as a civil society organization while openly proclaiming that their members are trained - even armed - for defense (disaster response, homeland security, law enforcement) tasks, and also citing the inadequacy of the police, the army, i.e. the state", they added.
They noted that this was done in accordance with a methodology which attempts to disguise different political aspirations as civilians based on the political and partisan divisions in society.
The emphasis on civility and the form of the association is therefore not only a means of avoiding legal pitfalls in the case of judicial registration of these associations, but also a political strategy.
The analysis shows that the activities of the Hungarian Guard are a risk-increasing factor for neighbourhood relations as well.
"In recent months, several neighboring states have also referred to the Hungarian Guard as a potential threat, and ultra-nationalist political actors in some neighboring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the establishment of the Hungarian Guard.
All this affects the political stability of the region", they added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not an isolated phenomenon in Eastern and Central Europe, so political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
As noted, the functioning of the Hungarian Guard is similar to, for example, the activity of the Bulgarian National Guard, which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The background to the formation of the Bulgarian Guard is the mass Roma riots that broke out in a district of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
The BNU took advantage of this and decided to form a guard, saying that the organization's purpose was "national self-defense".
For the past 17 years, they say, Bulgaria has been plagued by "gypsy terror", but the state has remained passive and indifferent.
The initiative has sparked a heated debate among the Bulgarian public.
As reported, the increased risk of ethnic clashes is indicated by the fact that some Bulgarian Roma organisations have announced the creation of their own resistance guards.
Since the Hungarian Guard's functioning so far shows similarities to the Bulgarian National Guard, it is not excluded that the Roma in Hungary will also respond to the threat in a similar way, by organizing their own self-defense.
Attila Juhász, research director at Political Capital, told the Telegraph that risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
As you said, they publish their risk analysis every year and if they find something that could affect the change in risk, they inform the public, as in this case by issuing a risk warning.
Not everywhere is red
In Hungary, the law specifies the days in red letters, and it has become common practice to rearrange the working day around holidays, with fewer days next year.
The EU and the US do not have a uniform celebration.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and working days.
The days of rest are usually associated with religious festivals and important historical events.
We also celebrate New Year's Eve, the last day of the new year and the first day of the new year, both days of work break - the latter just so that the New Year's workers can rest.
We have a total of 11 red letter holidays throughout the year.
National holidays are 15 March and 23 October, commemorating the 1848 revolution, and the 1956 revolution.
On August 20th, we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1st, we celebrate work, and on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, we have two-day festivals, Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our national, state, or even religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, it has become common practice to shift the workday in cases where we would only work one day before or after the red-lettered holiday.
True, the price of extended weekends is that we don't miss work and school on the Saturday before.
