After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Bad Arolsen archive, which documents the fate of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, has been made public.
The 47 million archival documents, which occupy 27 kilometres of shelves in Bad Arolsen, Hesse, were previously only available for 'humanitarian' purposes, i.e. only for individual and name-based access to former victims or their descendants.
In May 2006, the 11 States managing the archive - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed to open the archive to researchers and historians.
After all states ratified the convention, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the Bad Arolsen archive will allow historians to conduct research "on the health conditions of prisoners, camp residents and forced laborers", explains Reto Meistern, director of the archive managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, have opposed the release of the documents, as they contain names and therefore confidential information.
For example, some deported victims may have been suspected of homosexuality or mental disabilities.
Lists of concentration camps and arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo were compiled after the war for practical purposes, to search for civilians deported or sentenced to forced labor and possibly to provide evidence of their internment for compensation.
Bad Arolsen already has more than 300 permanent employees who handle tens of thousands of individual needs.
However, the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive is not considered significant by some in the scientific community.
"These documents contain basically nothing new", declared Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technical University of Berlin, in 2006.
