Congress approves the adoption of MiFID, which took effect on November 1st.
In parallel with the parliamentary proceedings, which ended today with the congressional vote approving the Senate amendments, the government has launched a public dialogue on the regulations that will underpin the law, so that both can be implemented before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups unanimously highlighted the efforts made by the Members of Parliament and the Senators in negotiating and agreeing on the most favourable rules for investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of companies, in order to ensure the efficient functioning of the market.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Act, will allow for the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, extending the supervisory powers of the Spanish National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors in the European Union.
The new Directive allows the provision of financial advisory services to companies specialising in this field, but also to natural or legal persons, and creates a new form of financial service enterprise (ESIS) in addition to securities firms, securities agencies and portfolio management companies, namely financial advisory firms (AFI).
In addition, the law increases the number of systems capable of executing transactions involving funds, thus adding to the regulated secondary markets multilateral trading platforms and internalisation systems for order execution, which compete with the current stock exchange operators.
The Law also requires investment firms to provide market information on the key aspects of their business profile, their risk-taking and risk management practices and to keep records of all transactions carried out to facilitate the control of the CNMV.
The Congressional Economic Committee introduced a number of amendments, most notably treating securitized debt as a "complex" financial instrument because of its high risk to investors, as was the case with the US subprime mortgage.
Secondly, the transposition of the Directive was also used to legally define the activities of those with a degree in economics and business, 30 years after the entry into force in 1977 of the Royal Decree defining the professional functions exclusively available to economists.
The Senate proposed the creation of new players in the financial sector, such as an intermediary agent, who works for someone else, does not need a CNMV authorisation and can market products or acquire clients for several investment companies at the same time.
