The three arrests were preceded by the arrest of six people last Monday in Galicia, Madrid and Murcia in connection with a case in which two hectares of agricultural land were converted into development land to allow the Galician firm Nuaria to build 4,000 apartments after illegally paying commissions to managers during their previous mandate.
Two other persons have not yet been arrested but are under investigation, according to the Totana Court No. 1.
The first six people arrested were handed over to the court.
Officials say former Totana mayor Juan Morales, now an independent MP for the People's Party, is also under investigation.
The ex-wife, who owns a real estate agency in Totana, is also under investigation, as is the former mayor's current girlfriend, who lives in the provincial capital of Murcia.
The director and owner of Nuaria Group, Manuel N.A., a lawyer and entrepreneur, was arrested in Nigrán (Pontevedra), together with Pablo José M.G., director of Suelo de Inmonuar, a company also belonging to Nuaria Group through which the bribery was carried out.
The investigation is being carried out by the Local Crime Unit of the Central Operational Unit of the Police, whose members carried out 11 house searches in addition to the arrests, mainly at companies linked to the arrested in Madrid, Vigo, Murcia, Pontevedra, Las Rozas (Madrid) and Totana.
In Totana, only one person was arrested: the owner of a well-known poultry company in the area, who may have been a mediator in the case.
The Nuaria Group would have created the largest residential park in the city of Totana, with 5,000 apartments, a golf course and two wellness hotels.
The company acquired 2.2 million square meters of land in Totana, which was redeveloped, doubling the population of the town of 25,000.
