New fears over Russian-Ukrainian gas dispute
The gas dispute between Ukraine and Russia has resumed, which may also affect Russian fuel to be supplied to Western Europe.
The majority of Russian gas exported to the European Union (EU) passes through Ukraine and disputes between the two nations are always a matter of great concern.
Kiev has stated that if Moscow raises the gas price to be paid by Ukrainians, they will also hit Russia with higher transit costs.
A previous dispute between the two countries last year led to a drop in supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow concerns an attempt by the Ukrainian government and Russian state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom to reach an agreement on the gas price that Ukraine will pay to Russia in 2008.
Gazprom stated that it would have to implement a 50% price increase on the 2008 agreement with Ukraine for gas produced from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts believe that this could mean a 40% price increase for Ukraine for the shipment from Gazprom.
"It is important that we argue in the negotiations in accordance with one of the most important transit states for natural gas", Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinah told Reuters news agency.
'Changes in gas prices should definitely be linked to the debate on the level of transit costs through Ukraine (and to Western Europe) '.
As a result of the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom closed the pipeline to Ukraine in January 2006.
This led to a domino effect in exports to Western Europe, which also led to a significant price depression.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of the gas supplies to the European Union.
Russia has the world's largest natural gas reserves, but much of it remains unexplored.
As a result, Gazprom is supplementing its gas supply with natural gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet states in Central Asia.
The NHS "is required to check foreign workers"
NHS committees in Scotland should improve their control of criminal records for workers from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
The proposal was made by the Auditor-General, Robert Black, after a foreign doctor was linked in Scotland to the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland did not have accurate data on the number of overseas workers.
However, it also identified key controls, which were properly implemented, in its report, through a sample of five health authorities.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the Auditor-General checked the list of employees recruited outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi-born doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep drove into the building's main terminal.
Abdullah was one of three doctors questioned by video link at the Old Bailey in October on charges of attempted car bombings in the UK.
For their staff from overseas countries, the NHS Committees should check before the start of employment whether the workers concerned have the necessary qualifications and experience and are authorised to work in the United Kingdom.
Although Disclosure Scotland is used by the Scottish Health Committees for criminal record verification purposes, the agency is not authorised to obtain information of this nature from outside the UK.
The report by the Auditor-General proposed, inter alia, that the committees introduce a Criminal Records Office guide to facilitate the employer's control processes with the various overseas countries.
"Although we found evidence of such checks in personnel records, they are not regularly carried out", says the report.
Black said that while NHS Scotland has a high standard of its own pre-employment screening process, he added: 'Our report highlights areas for improvement in the system to ensure we have up-to-date information on the number of overseas NHS staff.'
Dr Peter Terry, president of the BMA Scotland, said it was "extremely unrealistic" that pre-employment checks could be used to identify potential NHS employees who might commit terrorist acts in the future.
'The report shows that the pre-employment checks currently in place are working well in NHS Scotland and the value of the proposals is not yet transparent,' he added.
According to the Scottish Health Authority, the current number of overseas staff, mostly doctors and nurses, is 1,161.
However, the Auditor-General drew attention to the fact that the figures are likely to be higher, partly because the committees have problems identifying staff on indefinite leave.
The investigation also showed that the control procedures in place in the NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, the Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian are highly coordinated.
These procedures covered the checks of passports, work permits and documents proving professional qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently reviewing a directive and guidance on pre-employment checks on NHS overseas staff.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I am very pleased that this task has been accomplished following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
He added that the Scottish Government, in cooperation with the Health Committees, would take into account the recommendations in the report and ensure that the updated guidance on pre-employment checks for the entire workforce, including overseas workers, reflects best practice.
Joy Division is at the film awards show.
A biopic about the late Joy Division singer Ian Curtis, Control, has swept five awards at the British Independent Film Awards - including best picture.
The award was also given to the lead actor, Sam Riley, who worked in a warehouse before playing Curtis, and to director Anton Corbijn and supporting actor Toby Kebbell.
The Best Actress award went to Dame Judi Dench for her thriller "Details of a Scandal".
And the Variety Award for bringing British cinema into the international spotlight went to Daniel Craig, who played Bond.
The awards were presented at a ceremony at the Roundhouse in London.
"Control" follows Curtis' rise from the Joy Division heyday to his suicide in 1980 at the age of 23.
The black and white film, which also features The Killers, David Bowie and New Order on the soundtrack, cost just £3 million to make.
Dutch photographer Corbijn - who had previously made a name for himself with his cover of U2's "Joshua Tree" - still won two awards; best director and best newcomer director.
Another winner of the ceremony put rock music at the centre of the celebration; Julien Temple's film about Joe Strummer, the lead singer of the Clash, won the award for best documentary.
The Best Actor award went to Viggo Mortensen for his performance as the mob boss's chauffeur in the David Cronenberg-directed thriller "Killer Promises", set in London.
Ray Winstone, known for his tough-guy roles, has been awarded the Richard Harris Award for his outstanding contribution to the British film industry.
The 50-year-old actor, whose credits include Scum, The Hunger Games and Sexy Guy, is currently filming Indiana Jones and the Kingdom of the Crystal Skull.
Winstone is proud to receive the award named after his late star of "Camelot" and "Harry Potter" in 2002.
"People like me have been opened up by the likes of Richard Harris and Albert Finney", Winstone added.
"I feel very fortunate to have met Richard Harris on several occasions.
Richard Harris' style is close to my heart, he was a great actor of his age and I have a great deal of respect for him".
The selection of independent film awards, known as the Bifa, is decided by a panel of filmmakers, actors and festival organisers.
Bifa's supporters and patrons include Mike Figgis, Ken Loach, Ewan McGregor, Samantha Morton, Bill Nighy, Meera Syal and Michael Winterbottom.
In Saudi Arabia, 208 people arrested in connection with a terrorist plot
Saudi Arabia announced yesterday that 208 militants affiliated with terrorist cells were arrested for planning an imminent attack on an oil facility and several attacks on church members and security forces.
State television in the world's biggest oil exporter says one of the cells was trying to smuggle missiles.
Al-Qaeda supporters have launched a campaign against the monarchy, which has been an ally of the United States since the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
According to a television report, an eight-member cell led by a resident of foreign nationality is planning an attack on an oil facility in the Eastern Province.
Following the 2006 Al-Qaeda-led attack on the world's largest oil refinery in Abqaiq, Saudi Arabia has begun building a 35,000-strong rapid reaction force to protect the facilities.
According to a report quoting the interior minister, 18 of those arrested belong to a cell led by an illegal border crosser who is "a person specialized in missile launches".
The report also reported that the warriors tried to smuggle eight shells into the kingdom.
Twenty-two of those arrested were planning to assassinate church leaders and security forces.
The government has called on religious leaders to take tougher action to curb the influx of Saudis into Iraq to join al-Qaeda fighters fighting coalition forces and the US-backed Shiite Muslim government, which Saudi hardline Sunnis consider heretical.
Al-Qaeda fighters view a significant number of Saudi Arabia's religious leaders as being drawn into the government's policy of supporting the royal family that controls the government.
The group's fighters, encouraged by Saudi-born al-Qaeda leader Osama bin Laden's call to target the pro-Western Saudi government, have targeted foreign-inhabited settlements, government buildings and energy facilities.
"The security forces have made a tremendous effort over the past... five months", an interior ministry spokesman told state television.
The arrests also involved the capture of a 16-member "media group" in Medina, which was designed to spread "takfiri thinking", the ideology of radical Sunni Muslims who support violent action against Muslims branded as infidels and apostates.
The arrest also included 32 individuals accused of providing financial support to the militants.
The climate of Venus may provide a glimpse into the future of the Earth
Scientists yesterday concluded that Venus may have once provided a pleasant habitat.
Data from a European orbiting spacecraft suggests that this planet may be more like Earth's odd twin than previously thought.
Venus is Earth's nearest planetary neighbor.
The two planets are nearly the same size and orbit similar, although Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
Scientists now know that billions of years ago, Venus may have had very similar conditions to Earth, and even habitable conditions.
But with its explosive greenhouse effect of carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion from solar radiation, and the planet's slower rotation, Venus has taken a very different course.
Today, the planet is covered in water vapor, surface temperatures hot enough to melt lead, and devastated by hurricane-force winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express spacecraft, based on a year-long study of the planet, paint a sobering picture of how similar catastrophic climate changes could develop on Earth.
Fred Taylor, professor of physics at Oxford University and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is beginning to become clear why the climate of Venus differs so greatly from that of Earth, despite the fact that the two planets are otherwise very similar in structure.
"Our new data allow us to develop a scenario for how Venus formed billions of years ago when it was still capable of Earth-like habitable conditions.
