Another gulf lies before Gordon Brown; the way out is unchanged
Compared to the British political scandals, this one doesn't seem too spicy.
No one has betrayed his honor, no politician has had his Paris hotel bills exposed, no one has committed an extramarital scandal.
But the discovery that a wealthy businessman had secretly contributed more than £650,000 ($1.3 million) to Britain's ruling Labour Party under the name of others over a period of more than four years and that the party had not reported on it is one of the things that the outcast Gordon Brown would have done well without.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister lost the election and when his statement that the polls had no bearing on the outcome of the election, he thoughtlessly questioned the intellectual capacity of the British people, people still hoped that Brown would provide a strong and effective government.
Instead, as Vince Cable, the Liberal Democrat deputy leader, who has been making increasingly witty remarks, has noted, the once-dreaded Brown Stalin has turned into Mr. Bean.
The rescue of the failing Northern Rock Bank has put regulatory weaknesses and judgement gaps in the crossfire.
The sickening proposals to change the tax code have encouraged business interests to unite against the government.
The loss of personal information of 25 million people to the tax authorities has exposed an unimaginable level of administrative malpractice.
Three retired generals have been rioting in the House of Lords to protest cuts to the military budget, saying the position of Home Secretary is a part-time job.
And now here are the secret donations of David Abrahams; Peter Watt, the Labour Party secretary general (formerly chief administrative officer) has resigned.
These accidents don't mean Brown can't turn back on the road to the exit.
At the same time, governments can reach a point where control becomes impossible.
People do not like or trust politicians, but when a new group comes to power, they usually suspend their distrust.
But once it becomes clear that the prime minister is unlikely to be able to move things forward, and may not stay in office for long, the suspended mistrust ends: the civil service begins to leak, cabinet ministers get briefed, the press looks for bad news; the government becomes defensive and unable to concentrate.
In some ways, Brown is in a particularly difficult position because, unlike other political leaders, he is not considered "fresh blood".
As much as she wants to deny her relationship with Tony Blair, she was still his right hand.
The problems with Northern Rock and the IRS records, for example, relate to decisions made by Brown during his time as Treasury Secretary.
And while he was not directly involved in Blair's misdeeds - such as the protracted investigation into the link between the "nobility for money" case and political party funding - voters may rightly assume otherwise.
Although Brown's situation is uncomfortable, it's not as embarrassing as it looks.
The mishaps committed are not as frightening as those Tories portray.
As with Mr. Bean, no one died, no one was directly implicated.
And the compensation, painful as it may be, is the creation of the trends that Brown-based Stalin has always promised: reliable, solid and somewhat hard-line government.
A good example is the fuss over political donations.
Abrahams, a skeptic who likens his giving to charity, said that he did not want to be public about his good deeds.
Maybe so, but the decision was not his to make.
The law banning the anonymity of major political supporters is clear and clearly justified: the public has a right to know who is knocking on the door of the country's rulers.
Watt, who said he knew about Abrahams's move but was unaware of its illegal nature, will certainly be sweated during the interrogations, as will Jon Medleson, the Labour Party's chief funder, who learned of the confusing donations in October.
But there's no leads to Brown at this point, and there's no indication that he knew about these schemes, not even that the huge payments were made after Brown took office in June.
So far, the prime minister has done half of his job.
Although he was quick to condemn the party's violations, he weakened his resolve by resorting to familiar means, entrusting the investigation of the case to a committee headed by a retired bishop and a judge, for safety reasons.
In this story, the "lesson to be learned" is not too complicated.
In case of a violation, the police are responsible.
In addition, Brown has other things to do, such as appointing the chairman of an independent committee to negotiate administrative rules that has been running without a leader for six months or advancing effective reforms to political party funding.
This would require the hard-line Labour Party to work with the Tories and cut off special financial ties to the unions - that would be a hard barrier for the partisan Brown.
But you should face some facts about the party.
Polls show the Conservatives are now in a major lead; Brown has two years to win back voters; the only way to win is by impeccable integrity and strong competence.
Card sharks
Is the secondary mortgage crisis threatening the American credit card market?
If blood gets in the water, sharks will naturally appear nearby.
Now that the U.S. housing market is in trouble, predators are focusing on the nation's credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts estimate that if the mortgage crisis spreads to other forms of consumer credit, the credit card market could lose as much as $99 billion.
The signs of tension are clearly visible.
The write-down rate, which indicates the proportion of non-performing loans, and the default rate, which indicates the proportion of late payments of more than 30 days, have both increased.
HSBC reported a $1.4 billion loss in its U.S. consumer finance segment last month, in part due to financial weakness of cardholders.
But it's too early to panic.
The rate of write-offs and late payments remains low.
The Moody's default rate of 3,89% for the third quarter is one full percentage point below the historical average.
The decrease in rates is partly due to technical factors.
The change in the US individual insolvency rules in 2005 resulted in a sudden decrease in the number of insolvency filings, but at the same time caused a large loss in the credit card market; the number of bankruptcies (and thus the write-down rate) is expected to increase again, whether or not the total conditions for borrowing deteriorate.
The payment rate, which shows the percentage of monthly consumer repayments, is also solid on the market.
In addition, confidence in credit card-backed securities is also quite strong, despite the paralysis in other areas of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney at TowerGroup, a research firm, estimates that 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
The signs of the impact of the mortgage crisis on the credit card market are clear: consumers are increasing their credit card debt to pay down their mortgages.
However, card issuers primarily monitor cash flows and not asset values, so a fall in house prices does not necessarily change the creditworthiness of borrowers.
The situation may even be advantageous for the creditors.
If the property is worth less than the mortgage value, consumers are less incentivised to repay the loan; as a result, the repayment of credit card debt takes priority.
Changes in interest rates or credit limits also allow card issuers to adapt more quickly and flexibly to changing conditions than mortgage lenders.
In theory, this should reduce the risk of sudden price revaluations of the assets.
"It's unlikely that we'll ever wake up to a complete revaluation of loans", says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer of Capital One.
If a sudden subprime crisis in the credit card market is less likely, the risk of a gradual downturn is much higher.
If falling housing prices and a slump in credit push America into recession, the industry will undoubtedly face a dire future.
It's worth keeping an eye on those predatory finches.
British bankers pleaded guilty in the Enron case.
On Wednesday, three British bankers who were brought to trial for their role in a fraud involving the name of former Enron chief financial officer Andrew Faston pleaded guilty.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew initially pleaded not guilty to a seven-count fraud charge alleging they collaborated with Fastow in a covert fraud in 2000 to enrich themselves at the expense of their employers.
Their trial started in January.
But at a court hearing before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein, Jr., each pleaded guilty to one count of wire fraud.
Three former employees of the Greenwich NatWest division of the Royal Bank of Scotland Group have become known in Britain during the two-year extradition proceedings.
The investigation into the Enron collapse in 2001 is still pending in the United States.
The first indictment against them in 2002 alerted Fastow that he was one of the targets of a government investigation into the bankruptcy of Enron.
The three brokers, dubbed the "NatWest Three", allegedly traveled to Houston in 2000 to prepare the fraud with Fastow and Fastow's then-right-hand man, Michael Kopper.
Fastow, responsible for orchestrating the numerous frauds that bankrupted Enron, also controlled the Enron subsidiary in which Greenwich NatWest invested.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank was not aware of any stake in the subsidiary, but the three British men were well aware of the large stake.
A company controlled by Kopper bought the bank's $1 million stake in the subsidiary.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 to get a stake in this company.
The indictment alleges that Fastow falsely informed Enron that the energy company was buying a $20 million stake in a subsidiary from Greenwich NatWest.
But in reality, the $20 million was in the hands of British bankers, Fastow and others.
The prosecution believes the bankers made $7.3 million, while Fastow, Kopper and others made $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy to cause the collapse of Enron.
The British three were arrested three months later.
Fastow is currently serving a six-year sentence at a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a sentence of three years and one month in a Texas prison.
The three Englishmen were released on bail of $1 million each and are in the United States for the duration of the trial.
Enron, the seventh-largest American company ever, filed for bankruptcy in December 2001 after years of accounting tricks failed to cover up the millions of dollars in debt and the profitable but actually loss-making businesses it had accumulated.
The collapse has resulted in thousands of job losses, a market value of more than $60 billion, and a decline in the value of pension funds of more than $2 billion.
Kenneth Lay, founder of Enron and former CEO Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year of complicity in the company's bankruptcy.
Skilling is currently serving his sentence of more than 24 years in prison.
Lay's charges of conspiracy, fraud and other charges were dropped after his death last year.
