Expectations of Fed rate cuts are driving stock markets around the world into a tailspin
Shares on both sides of the Atlantic jumped yesterday after reassuring statements from the vice president of the Federal Reserve raised hopes that the Fed will try to ease investment opportunities with further rate cuts.
Stock markets in London, New York and across Europe have been buoyed by Donald Kohn, a right-hand man to Fed Chairman Ben Bernanke, who said executives must respond "flexibly and pragmatically" to ongoing financial market turmoil.
In addition to the clear aim of Kohn to calm the markets amid signs of a resurgent credit crisis, he stated that the current unrest had 'partly reversed the market development achieved at the end of September and October'.
It said that if the increased confusion persists, it could increase the possibility of further restrictions on credit conditions for households and companies.
The statements were interpreted by investors as the Fed's readiness to inject fresh capital into US markets or even further interest rate cuts to stabilize credit conditions.
The announcements also reassured Wall Street, which has been hit by a number of recent bad news stories about the U.S. economy, including a record negative number of U.S. home sales.
The side effect of the financial turmoil was reinforced by the announcement by investment bank Bear Stearns that it would cut 650 jobs, or 4% of its global workforce, as part of cost-cutting to offset losses in the US secondary mortgage sector.
The above measure affects a total of 20 jobs at the London headquarters, which employs 1500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average index rose 331 points, 2.55 percent, to close at 13,289.40, while the broader S&P 500 index rose 2.65 percent.
