Buses are taking refugees home to work and fight al-Qaeda.
Yesterday, the first buses arrived from Syria to Baghdad with Iraqi refugees who had run out of money or their visas had expired or who were hoping that the city would be restored to order.
Some of them have returned to fight the soldiers who drove them from their homes.
The bus station in Mansour was already filled with refugees returning from Syria and Jordan before a government convoy of 800 people from Damascus arrived, several dozen buses full.
"I decided to go to Syria after many doctors were killed in Baghdad", said Sunni doctor Sabah al-Qubaisi.
"I came back today because I saw on TV and in the newspapers what happened in Baghdad and that the city is now safe.
"They say the Mahdi army has stopped killing people", he added, referring to the militia cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who is currently halting the Shiite army.
Qassim al-Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher from Amariyah, a predominantly Sunni town, returned home with two children after failing to renew his Syrian visa and because the regime there prevented Iraqis from taking up work.
Neighbors in Amarya's Shiite neighborhood called him and urged him to return home, saying that with the help of US-backed troops, they had driven al-Qaeda from their stronghold in the western part of the capital.
One of the first to arrive from Jordan was a Sunni and Shiite tribal leader who fled a shelling of his home in Sleikh, north of Baghdad, after he began urging his fellow citizens to fight against al-Qaeda.
He came back to fight.
"Two days ago, my friends called me and said they had formed an anti-Al Qaeda militia in Sleikh and needed my support and that of my sons.
That's why I came back today", said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many spoke of the peace that had been consolidated in the capital since the entry of American troops and the attraction of armed civilian forces working with the Americans.
But many more have been forced to return home from Damascus because of visa and financial problems.
Salaam al-Samarrai, 51, a father of three, voiced a view widely held among refugees that Shia Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki had asked the Syrian government to deny refugees visas in order to force them to return.
It is estimated that more than two and a half million people have fled the death squads operating in the country.
"Everything was fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and pressured the government not to issue more visas to Iraqis to allow them to move back home", the Sunni pensioner said.
"I can't trust a government that supports the criminals who burned down my house after I escaped".
One reason for the easing of violence is that Sunnis have been driven out of Shia areas, while Shia have also been driven out of Sunni-populated areas, and as a result, tensions have eased in many areas.
Many fear that the sudden arrival of refugees will stir up new tensions, possibly leading to more fighting.
Small Saarland - training at all levels
The smallest federal state is a leader in vocational training and its higher education is internationally oriented.
In one area of training, rural Saar people face the same deficit as the rest of the country.
"Yesterday I explained for the 50th time to a person outside the Saarland that we are not French", is the self-deprecating slogan on the posters of the smallest federal state's 50th birthday.
At the same time, France and Luxembourg play an important role in the education system of the Saarland, which ranks fifth in the surveys of the German Economic Institute (IW) in Cologne.
