Saarbrücken University was founded by the French in 1948.
Students here can still graduate with a double or even triple degree.
Accordingly, the proportion of foreign students is high at 15.6%.
However, even for those who want to study in the Saarland, the Saarland's colleges and universities are above average attractive - many of them do not have a high school diploma.
"The Saar region is taking advantage of the opportunities for vocational training", explains Axel Plünnecke, an education expert at the German Economic Institute.
More than one fifth of young people are eligible for further education in vocational schools, which is more than seven per cent higher than the federal average in the Saarland.
The combined vocational and higher education options are also well developed.
The infrastructure for dual studies is the second largest in Germany in terms of population.
However, despite practice-oriented training and growing interest, the number of graduates in engineering has fallen by a third in recent years.
