Venus is Earth's evil twin
Despite its harsh atmosphere, Venus is more Earthlike than previously thought: In its atmosphere, the European Venus Express spacecraft has detected lightning strikes, and at its poles, winds like those that occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have speculated that lightning strikes on Venus.
The European spacecraft "Venus Express" has provided evidence - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus is transmitted from cloud to cloud at a height of 35 miles [56 km], reports Christopher Russell, a researcher at the University of California, Los Angeles, in the science magazine Nature.
The famous "soup theory" says that lightning caused life on Earth: The theory is that storms set off reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If life ever existed, it must have been very early", explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
At present, there is little chance of life on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is around 100 times denser than on Earth, and temperatures sometimes reach 500 degrees Fahrenheit [500°C].
"Venus may be Earth's infernal twin, but it is still its twin", Russell said.
The main question for the ESA mission is why Venus, so similar in mass and size to Earth, is on a completely different path of evolution.
The launch of the Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in the search for Venus, for no probe has been on a mission to find this planet since the early 1990s.
Recent research results, presented in several Nature articles, are proving that Venus is not just unique in the solar system.
"They also indicate that the neighboring planet is more similar to Earth than we first thought", Esa said.
In addition to the already familiar Arctic wind, researchers have discovered an even faster-moving cloudburst in the South Pole.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents of the Earth's winter hemisphere, says a team led by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second innermost planet in the solar system has a mass almost equal to that of the earth and is nearly the size of the earth at 7,500 miles [12,100 km] in diameter.
Also called the Morning Star, it takes just 225 days to circle the sun.
However, it orbits its own equator much more slowly, with a Venus day lasting 243 Earth days.
Although Venus' surface temperature of 1,500 degrees Fahrenheit [460°C], coupled with its 92 bar pressure, is hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that both planets formed under very similar conditions.
On both of them, water accumulated, which remained on Earth as an ocean, while on Venus it was released into the universe.
And while on Earth, carbon dioxide is bound in carbonate rocks, on Venus, it makes up most of the atmosphere.
