These aren't Warhol boxes.
If you think of Sweden and its woods, you're thinking of Ike, not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
The wooden boxes now being made in Sweden cast a dark shadow over Warhol's catalogue.
Most of the 94 'Stockholm-type' Brillo Boxes listed here are counterfeit.
After the Swedish newspaper Expressen questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo Boxes a few months ago, an internal investigation at Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now produced a sobering result: The six Brillo Boxes donated to Moderna Museet in 1995 by Pontus Hultén, a former museum director, and most likely a large part of the hundreds of other "Stockholm-type" Brillo Boxes on the international art market.
The history is a long and complicated chain of artistic and curatorial displays.
Warhol created the first "Brillo Boxait" in New York in 1964, painted wooden boxes based on the red, blue, and white design of the "Brillo" soap box.
A 1968 exhibition of his work at Moderna Museet, with Warhol's permission, featured hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These (for cost-saving reasons) did not originate from Warhol, but were shipped directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It wasn't artworks, it was their templates, simple exhibits.
However, Warhol granted permission in 1968 for some Brillo woodcuts to be made in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses now speak of fifteen boxes that were then certified as Original Andy Warhol Brillo-Box under the "Stockholm type" designation and have rightfully entered the history of art and auction.
Some of them sold for over $100,000.
The problem, however, was that Pontus Hultén, the legendary museum director, later falsely claimed that in 1968 a hundred wooden wheels were made and exhibited in Sweden, which he then left to Warhol.
In fact, Hultén's 105 cases were only produced in 1990 in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
But by this time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined three Swedish private boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968, in addition to the six Brillo Boxes owned by the museum. The pressed sheets were first ground and sanded, then the white oil paint was brushed.
The structure of the 1990 copies, however, suggests that the paint was applied directly to the cutting board with a paint roller, without a backing - and it is not oil, but acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authenticated by the artist and should therefore be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol Brillo Boxes", says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museum. "Unless the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York decides otherwise, the Moderna Museum will classify the official box in its collection as a copy/exhibition item".
The Authentication Board, of course, announced back in June that it was investigating "serious allegations" about soapbox sales.
But since then, they have been enveloped in relentless silence.
